{{Infobox War on Terror detainee | name = Ahmed Adil | image = | image_size = 203px | caption = Ahmed Adil | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1973}} | birth_place = [[Kashgar]], [[China]] | death_date = | death_place = | detained_at = [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo]] | id_number = 260 | group = | alias = | charge = No charge (held in [[extrajudicial detention]]) | penalty = | status = Transferred to a refugee camp in Albania. | occupation = | spouse = | parents = | children = }} '''Ahmed Adil''' is a citizen of [[China]] who was held in [[extrajudicial]] detention in the [[United States]] [[Guantanamo Bay detainment camp]]s, in [[Cuba]].<ref name=DoDList2> {{cite web | url=http://www.dod.mil/news/May2006/d20060515%20List.pdf | title=List of Individuals Detained by the Department of Defense at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba from January 2002 through May 15, 2006 | publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] | accessdate=2006-05-15
}}</ref> Adil's Guantanamo [[Internment Serial Number]] was 260. American [[intelligence analysts]] estimate he was born in 1973, in [[Kashgar]], China.
Adil is one of approximately two dozen detainees from the [[Uyghur people|Uyghur]] ethnic group.<ref>[http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FK04Ad02.html China's Uighurs trapped at Guantanamo] {{webarchive |url=https://www.webcitation.org/5iiEnVC9Y?url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FK04Ad02.html |date=2009-08-01 }}, ''[[Asia Times]]'', November 4, 2004</ref> Adil is one of approximately half a dozen Uyghurs whose [[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]s determined they were not enemy combatants after all.<ref name=WapoNlec>{{cite web |url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/guantanamo/nlec/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811015712/http://projects.washingtonpost.com/guantanamo/nlec/ |archivedate=11 August 2006 |title=Guantanamo Bay Detainees {{sic|nolink=y|Classifed}} as 'No Longer Enemy Combatants' |publisher= ''[[Washington Post]]'' }}</ref><ref name=DoDNlecList20071119> {{cite news | url= | title=Detainees Found to No Longer Meet the Definition of "Enemy Combatant" during Combatant Status Review Tribunals Held at Guantanamo | publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] | author= | date=November 19, 2007
}}</ref> Five of the Uyghurs were transferred to [[Albania]].<ref name=BBC20070111> {{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6189517.stm | title=Albanian fix for Guantanamo Dilemma | publisher=BBC | date=January 11, 2007 | accessdate=2008-04-25 | first=Neil | last=Arun }}</ref> Several others had new Tribunals convened that reversed the earlier determination.<ref name="No-hearing_hearings"> {{cite web | url=http://law.shu.edu/news/final_no_hearing_hearings_report.pdf | title=No-hearing hearings | page=17 | author=Mark Denbeaux | author-link=Mark Denbeaux | author2=Joshua Denbeaux | author2-link=Joshua Denbeaux | author3=David Gratz | author4=John Gregorek | author5=Matthew Darby | author6=Shana Edwards | author7=Shane Hartman | author8=Daniel Mann | author9=Megan Sassaman | author10=Helen Skinner | last-author-amp=yes | publisher=[[Seton Hall University]] School of Law | accessdate=April 2, 2007 }}</ref>
