'''Gleb Svyatoslavich''' ({{circa}} 1052&nbsp;– 30 May 1078) was [[Prince of Tmutarakan]] and [[Principality of Novgorod|Novgorod]]. He ruled Tmutarakan under the overall authority of his father [[Sviatoslav II of Kiev|Sviatoslav Iaroslavich]], [[Prince of Chernigov]]. He was twice expelled from his principality by one of his cousins [[Rostislav of Tmutarakan|Rostislav Vladimirovich]].

His father appointed him prince of Novgorod in 1067 or 1068. He suppressed a rebellion incited by a sorcerer against the [[Diocese of Novgorod and Staraya Russa|bishop of the town]]. Later he was expelled from Novgorod, and was killed by the [[Chudes]]. The ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]'' writes that he "was kindly toward the poor and hospitable to strangers, zealous toward the church, warm in faith, peaceful, and fair in appearance".<ref>''Russian Primary Chronicle'' (year 6586), p. 165.</ref>{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=143}}

==Early life==
Gleb was the eldest of the fours sons of [[Sviatoslav II of Kiev|Sviatoslav Iaroslavich]], [[Prince of Chernigov]] by his first wife, Killikiya.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=38-39}} According to historian Martin Dimnik, Gleb was born around 1049.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=40}} He was named after his father's holy uncle, [[Boris and Gleb|Gleb]].{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=78}} His father appointed him to rule [[Tmutarakan]],{{sfn|Vernadsky|1948|p=84}} an important port by the [[Strait of Kerch]], but the year of his appointment is unknown.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=55-56}}

==Prince of Tmutarakan==

According to the ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]'', Gleb's cousin [[Rostislav of Tmutarakan|Rostislav Vladimirovich]] "fled to Tmutorakan"<ref name="Russian_Primary_Chronicle_6572_144">''Russian Primary Chronicle'' (year 6572), p. 144.</ref> in 1064.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=58}} He expelled Gleb from Tmutorakan and "occupied his principate for himself".<ref name="Russian_Primary_Chronicle_6572_144"/>{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=58}}{{sfn|Martin|1993|p=41}} Although Gleb was restored by his father in 1065, once Sviatoslav Iaroslavich had returned with his army to [[Chernigov]], Rostislav invaded again and displaced Gleb from power once more.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=58}}{{sfn|Vernadsky|1948|p=85}}

However, the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] ''[[katepano]]'' or governor of [[Cherson (theme)|Cherson]] poisoned Rostislav who died on 3 February 1067.{{sfn|Martin|1993|p=41}}{{sfn|Vernadsky|1948|p=85}}{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=59}} According to the ''Life of Feodosy'', the citizens of Tmutorakan requested the monk Nikon the Great to persuade Sviatoslav Iaroslavich to again appoint Gleb as their prince.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=64}} The saintly monk succeeded and Gleb returned to Tmutarakan.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=64}} According to the inscription of the "[[Stone of Tmutarakan]]", Gleb had the width of the frozen Strait of Kerch measured in the winter of 1067-68.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=64-65}}

==Prince of Novgorod==
[[File:Principalities of Kievan Rus' (1054-1132).jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=Map of the Kievan Rus' | Principalities in the [[Kievan Rus']] (1054-1132)]]
Gleb was transferred{{mdash}}according to historian Martin Dimnik, by his father{{mdash}}from Tmutarakan to [[Novgorod]] in 1067 or 1068.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=64-65}} A distant relative of his, [[Vseslav of Polotsk|Vseslav Briacheslavich]] lay siege to Novgorod "on October 23, the day of the [[Jesus|Lord]]'s brother, [[James the Just|St James]], a Friday, at the sixth hour of the day",<ref>''The Chronicle of Novgorod'' (year AD 1068 AM 6576), p. 5.</ref> according to the ''[[Novgorod First Chronicle|Chronicle of Novgorod]]''.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=71-72}} However, Gleb and the Novgorodians routed him on the brook Gzen near the town.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=72}}{{sfn|Franklin|Shepard|1996|p=256}}

Gleb's rule in Novgorod was confirmed when his father became the [[Grand Prince of Kiev]] in 1073.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=93}} According to the [[Hypatian Codex|Hypatian version]] of the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'', Gleb visited his father in [[Kiev]] and witnessed the death of the saintly Abbot [[Theodosius of Kiev|Feodosy]] of the Monastery of the Caves in 1074.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=95}} He seems to have been on friendly terms with his cousin, [[Vladimir Monomach]] whose first son was born in his court at Novgorod.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=97}} A late source{{mdash}}[[Vasily Tatishchev]]'s compilation of medieval chronicles{{mdash}}writes that Sviatoslav Iaroslavich appointed Gleb and Vladimir Monomach to command the Rus' troops sent to fight against the [[Bulgarians]] at [[Kherson|Cherson]] upon the request of the [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Michael VII Ducas]], but the source's reliability is doubtful.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=xv-xvi, 99}}

The ''Russian Primary Source'' narrates that a "[[Magician (paranormal)|magician]]"<ref name="Russian_Primary_Chronicle_6579_154">''Russian Primary Chronicle'' (year 6579), p. 154.</ref> arrived in Novgorod and stirred up the townsfolk against the [[Diocese of Novgorod and Staraya Russa|bishop]].{{sfn|Franklin|Shepard|1996|p=229}} The magician planned to murder the prelate but Gleb and his ''[[druzhina]]'' or retinue remained loyal to him.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=108}} Gleb dared the sorcerer who had stated that he could foretell the future to predict "what was about to happen that very day",<ref name="Russian_Primary_Chronicle_6579_154"/> according to the ''Russian Primary Chronicle''.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=108}} The magician declared that he would "perform great miracles",<ref name="Russian_Primary_Chronicle_6579_154"/> but Gleb pull out an axe from his cloth and killed him.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=108}} After the magician's death, his followers broke up.{{sfn|Franklin|Shepard|1996|p=246}}{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=108}}

Gleb's father died on 27 December 1076.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=127}} According to Novgorodian sources, the citizens of the town rose in revolt and dethroned Gleb in 1078.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=144}}{{sfn|Franklin|Shepard|1996|p=260}} He fled beyond the lands beyond the river [[Vishera River (Novgorod Oblast)|Volkhov]], known as Zavoloch'e, where the [[Chudes]] killed him on 30 May.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|pp=143-144}} His body was transferred to Chernigov where he was buried in the Holy Savior Cathedral on 23 July.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=143}} No source makes mention of Roman's marriage or his children, suggesting that he never married and died childless.{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=41}}

