{{Other uses|City of Everett (disambiguation)}}
{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox Ship Image |Ship image =City of Everett whaleback.jpg |Ship caption =The ''City of Everett'' under construction }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header = |Ship country = United States |Ship flag = {{USN flag|1936}} |Ship name = ''City of Everett'' |Ship owner = |Ship operator = |Ship ordered = |Ship builder = Everett Shipyards |Ship yard number = |Ship laid down = |Ship launched = 1894 |Ship completed = |Ship christened = |Ship out of service = 1923 |Ship homeport = |Ship fate = foundered in Gulf of Mexico 1923 |Ship notes = }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header = |Header caption = |Ship class = |Ship tonnage = |Ship displacement = |Ship length ={{convert|346|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam = {{convert|42|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship height ={{convert|13.58|ft|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draft = |Ship depth = |Ship power = |Ship propulsion = |Ship speed = |Ship capacity = |Ship crew = |Ship notes = only whaleback to travel in the [[Suez Canal]]<ref name="Zoss"/> }} |}
The '''SS ''City of Everett''''' was an important [[whaleback]] steamship. She sailed from 1894 until 1923, and was the first U.S. steamship to pass through the [[Suez Canal]], as well as the first to circumnavigate the globe.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4442/is_200410/ai_n16065472/pg_2 | work=Sea Classics | title=LAST of the WHALEBACKS | year=2004}}</ref> Her radio call letters were GF and her signal letters KMCQ.
==Origin== In the 1890s, [[Alexander McDougall (1845-1923)|Alexander McDougall]], the originator of the whaleback ship design, wanted to build ships in [[Washington (state)|Washington]], on the Pacific Coast. His steamer {{SS |Charles W. Wetmore}} (1891 – 265&nbsp;ft) became the first lake vessel to leave the [[Great Lakes]] when she took a load of grain from Duluth to Liverpool, England, shooting the St. Lawrence rapids in the process. ''Wetmore'' was sent around [[Cape Horn]] with a load of supplies for the establishment of a shipbuilding colony near [[Everett, Washington]]. From parts she carried, the ''City of Everett'' was built, commissioned in 1894. Intended to be the first of a line of whaleback ships built out of the facility in Everett, changing fortunes resulted in her being the only ship produced there by McDougall's ill-fated company.
==Her career== The unarmed steamer “captured” the City of [[Malaga, Spain]], when it entered the harbor seeking fresh water, which occasioned a surrender by the city’s inhabitants during the [[Spanish–American War]].<ref name="Zoss">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9zP75S5HJA8C&printsec=frontcover&dq |isbn=9781439635056|title=McDougall’s Great Lakes Whalebacks |first1=Neel R. |last1=Zoss |date=August 15, 2007 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]}}</ref>[[File:City of Everett.jpg|thumb|left|The ''City of Everett'' underway]]
On 8 September 1902, ''City of Everett'' suffered an explosion while loading at [[Port Arthur, Texas]]. Her captain, a mate, and several crew members were seriously injured; the resulting fire engulfed not only the ship, but also destroyed the docks and wharves of the Texas Company (later known as [[Texaco]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldandsold.com/articles11/port-arthur-7.shtml|title=Bulls And Bears|website=www.oldandsold.com}}</ref>
In January 1905, ''City of Everett'' collided with the Norwegian steam freighter ''Leif Eriksson'' north of [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. ''Leif Eriksson'' took on water through a deep gash in her hull, and sank in less than 10 minutes with the loss of two lives.<ref>{{cite web |title=25 September 2007: Identification of the "Anchor Wreck" |publisher=Association of Underwater Explorers |author=Barnette, Michael C. |url=http://uwex.us/AUEaugust07.htm |year=2007 |accessdate=2008-09-06 |authorlink=Michael C. Barnette }}</ref>
Near [[Nantucket]] on 23 January 1909, ''City of Everett'' heard a [[CQD|distress signal]] from the [[RMS Republic|RMS ''Republic'']], which was taking on water following a collision. Captain Thomas Fenlon of the ''City of Everett'' twice offered his ship's considerable pumping and towing abilities, but with assistance reportedly on the way from the [[White Star Line]], ''Republic'' declined.<ref name="nytimes">https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/01/27/101864346.pdf ''New York Times article'', 26 January 1909 ''Could Have Saved Republic, He Says"</ref> Fog delayed tugs of the White Star Line, and towing efforts by the smaller US Coast Guard cutter [[USCGC Gresham (WPG-85)|''Gresham'']] failed. ''Republic'' sank the next day. Newspapers at the time reported that if the White Star Line had been successful in recovering the ''Republic'' with company ships, instead of using a third-party salvor, it could have recouped some of its salvage expenses from the owners of the recovered cargo aboard the ''Republic''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms-republic.com/sal01.html|title=Practically Unsinkable - RMS - Republic|website=www.rms-republic.com}}</ref> The inference was that ''Republic's'' captain had refused aid merely to prevent another company from sharing the salvage award if the ship were to be saved. ''Everett's'' Captain Fenlon maintained that, as ''Republic'' had remained afloat until the day after the collision, she could have been saved if she had accepted a tow from ''City of Everett'', stating that his boat was "built for ocean towing" and was equipped with "tremendously powerful machinery and towing cables seven inches (178 mm) in diameter", as well as pumps with a capacity of "two million gallons an hour".<ref name="nytimes"/>
While carrying [[molasses]] from [[Santiago, Cuba]] to [[New Orleans]] on 11 October 1923, ''City of Everett'' [[shipwreck|foundered]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. All 26 people on board died in the sinking.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://visseraa.piranho.de/International/id614.htm|title=piranho|website=visseraa.piranho.de}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==Discovery of the shipwreck ''City of Everett''== On September 11, 2010, divers from the Association of Underwater Explorers, [[Michael C. Barnette|Michael Barnette]] and Joe Citelli, identified the wreck of the ''City of Everett'' resting in approximately {{convert|400|ft|m}} of sea water {{convert|120|nmi|km}} off Florida in the Gulf of Mexico.<ref name=Tomalin10>{{cite newspaper |author=Tomalin, Terry |title=Fishermen find big one that didn't get away: a steamship resting miles off Naples |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |url=http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/fishermen-find-big-one-that-didnt-get-away-a-steamship-resting-miles-off/1139287 |date=2010-12-12 |accessdate=2010-12-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215160127/http://www.tampabay.com/features/humaninterest/fishermen-find-big-one-that-didnt-get-away-a-steamship-resting-miles-off/1139287 |archive-date=2010-12-15 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name=EverettHerald>{{cite news |author=Smith, Debra |title=Divers may have found ship built in Everett in 1894. |publisher=The Herald |location=Everett, Washington |url=http://www.heraldnet.com/article/20110102/NEWS01/701029857 |date=2011-01-02 |accessdate=2011-01-02}}</ref>
