'''Vukašin Šoškoćanin''' ({{lang-sr|Вукашин Шошкоћанин}}; 24 June 1958 – 15 May 1991) was a [[Serbs of Croatia|Croatian Serb]] war commander. He was president of the [[Borovo, Croatia|Borovo commune]] and commander of the [[Territorial Defense Forces (Yugoslavia)|Borovo Selo Territorial Defense Force]] during the [[Croatian War of Independence|Croatian War]]. Born to Milan and Ljubica Šoškoćanin on 24 June 1958, Vukašin had two brothers, Radovan and Dušan. He became a member of the [[Serb Democratic Party (Croatia)|Serb Democratic Party]] in 1990.<ref>[http://www.mup.hr/main.aspx?id=10351 Profile], mup.hr; accessed 8 April 2015.{{hr icon}}</ref> Before the war, he was a [[Paraveterinary workers|veterinary technician]] in [[Vukovar]].{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}

Circumstances surrounding his death are largely unknown. On 15 May 1991 at around 10:30 AM, while returning from a visit to a refugee camp in [[Vojvodina]], he drowned in the [[Danube|Danube river]] in a "boating accident."<ref name="Deep Emotion Beneath Belgrade's Calm">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1991-05-26/news/25799026_1_serbs-croatia-civil-war|author=Dan Stets, ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''|title=Deep Emotion Beneath Belgrade's Calm|accessdate=20 August 2014|date=26 May 1991}}</ref> 

[[Milan Paroški]] publicly questioned the official cause of death and claimed that [[Frogman|frogmen]] (either the [[Yugoslav Navy|Yugoslav River Flotilla]] or the [[State Security Service (Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia)|Serbian State Security]]) were responsible for Šoškoćanin's death.<ref name="pogledi"/> Paroški also claimed that Šoškoćanin was "an excellent swimmer."<ref name="pogledi">''[[Pogledi]]'', issue number 138, pp. 16-17, 9 March 1993; YU {{ISSN|0353-3832}}</ref> His death is still labeled under "mysterious circumstances."<ref>http://www.b92.net/specijal/vukovar-eng/press13.php</ref>

After his death, an elementary school in Borovo was named in his honour.<ref>[http://www.udbina.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1199:godinjica-otpora-u-borovom-selu-borovo-selo-2-maja&catid=108:domovinski-rat&Itemid=135 School in Borovo named after Šoškoćanin], udbina.com; accessed 8 April 2015. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104075840/http://www.udbina.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1199%3Agodinjica-otpora-u-borovom-selu-borovo-selo-2-maja&catid=108%3Adomovinski-rat&Itemid=135 |date=4 November 2013 }}</ref> He was posthumously awarded the title of "Hero of the People" in [[Beli Manastir]] on 25 September 1991.<ref>[http://blog.vecernji.hr/sandra-sabljak/2011/04/23/sramota-spomenici-koji-velicaju-krvnika-a-omalovazavaju-zrtvu Profile], blog.vecernji.hr; accessed 8 April 2015.{{hr icon}}</ref>

